<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-fundamental-theorem-of-calculus"
  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      We now return to the theme announced at the end of
      <xref ref="sec-applications-of-differentiation"/>: differentiation and
      integration are inverse processes, at least under suitable hypotheses.
      We present the theorem in two standard forms.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-indefinite-integrals">
    <title>Indefinite Integrals</title>

    <p>
      Let <m>f \in R[a,b]</m>. For each <m>c \in [a,b]</m>, the function
      <md>
        x \mapsto \int_c^x f(t)\,dt
      </md>
      is called the <term>indefinite integral</term><idx><h>integral</h><h>indefinite</h></idx>
      of <m>f</m> with <term>base point</term><idx><h>integral</h><h>base point</h></idx>
      <m>c</m>.
    </p>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-ftc-second-form">
      <title>Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (Second Form)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \in R[a,b]</m>, and define
          <md>
            F(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt.
          </md>
          Then <m>F</m> is Lipschitz continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>. Moreover, if
          <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>x_0 \in [a,b]</m>, then <m>F</m> is
          differentiable at <m>x_0</m> and
          <md>
            F'(x_0)=f(x_0).
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Since <m>f</m> is integrable on <m>[a,b]</m>, it is bounded. Choose
          <m>M \ge 0</m> such that <m>|f(x)| \le M</m> for every
          <m>x \in [a,b]</m>. Let <m>x,x' \in [a,b]</m>. If <m>x \lt x'</m>,
          then part (3) of <xref ref="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral"
          text="title"/> gives
          <md>
            F(x')-F(x)=\int_x^{x'} f(t)\,dt.
          </md>
          Therefore, by part (4) of the same theorem,
          <md>
            |F(x')-F(x)|
            =
            \left|\int_x^{x'} f(t)\,dt\right|
            \le
            M|x'-x|.
          </md>
          The same inequality is trivial if <m>x=x'</m>, and it follows by
          symmetry when <m>x' \lt x</m>. Thus <m>F</m> is Lipschitz
          continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Now suppose that <m>f</m> is continuous at <m>x_0 \in [a,b]</m>. Let
          <md>
            \varphi(x)=
            \begin{cases}
              \dfrac{1}{x-x_0}\int_{x_0}^{x} f(t)\,dt &amp; \text{if } x \ne x_0,\\
              f(x_0) &amp; \text{if } x=x_0.
            \end{cases}
          </md>
          Then
          <md>
            F(x)-F(x_0)=\varphi(x)(x-x_0)
          </md>
          for every <m>x \in [a,b]</m>. We will prove that <m>\varphi</m> is
          continuous at <m>x_0</m>. Let <m>\varepsilon \gt 0</m>. There exists
          <m>\delta \gt 0</m> such that
          <md>
            |f(t)-f(x_0)| \lt \varepsilon
          </md>
          whenever <m>t \in [a,b]</m> and <m>|t-x_0| \lt \delta</m>. If
          <m>x \in [a,b]</m> with <m>0 \lt |x-x_0| \lt \delta</m>, then
          <md>
            \begin{aligned}
            |\varphi(x)-\varphi(x_0)|
            &amp;=
            \left|
            \frac{1}{x-x_0}\int_{x_0}^{x} f(t)\,dt
            -
            \frac{1}{x-x_0}\int_{x_0}^{x} f(x_0)\,dt
            \right| \\
            &amp;\le
            \frac{1}{|x-x_0|}
            \int_{\min\{x,x_0\}}^{\max\{x,x_0\}} |f(t)-f(x_0)|\,dt \\
            &amp;\lt
            \frac{1}{|x-x_0|}\varepsilon |x-x_0|
            =
            \varepsilon.
            \end{aligned}
          </md>
          Thus <m>\varphi(x) \to \varphi(x_0)</m> as <m>x \to x_0</m>, so
          <m>\varphi</m> is continuous at <m>x_0</m>. By Carathéodory's
          Criterion (<xref ref="prop-caratheodory-criterion"/>), it follows
          that <m>F</m> is differentiable at <m>x_0</m> and
          <m>F'(x_0)=\varphi(x_0)=f(x_0)</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-continuous-functions-have-primitives">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>f \in C[a,b]</m>, then the indefinite integral
          <md>
            F(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt
          </md>
          is an antiderivative, or <term>primitive</term><idx>primitive</idx>,
          of <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="thm-continuous-function-integrable" text="title"/>,
          every continuous function on <m>[a,b]</m> is Riemann integrable.
          Therefore <xref ref="thm-ftc-second-form" text="title"/> applies at
          every point of <m>[a,b]</m> and yields <m>F'=f</m>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <p>
      In general, however, an indefinite integral need not be differentiable
      at every point, and even when it is differentiable at a point, its
      derivative there need not equal the original integrand.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-ftc-signum-absolute-value">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the signum function
          <md>
            \operatorname{sgn}(x)=
            \begin{cases}
              1 &amp; \text{if } x \gt 0,\\
              0 &amp; \text{if } x=0,\\
              -1 &amp; \text{if } x \lt 0.
            \end{cases}
          </md>
          Since this is a step function, it is integrable on <m>[-1,1]</m>.
          Its indefinite integral with base point <m>0</m> is
          <md>
            F(x)=\int_0^x \operatorname{sgn}(t)\,dt=|x|.
          </md>
          The function <m>|x|</m> is not differentiable at <m>0</m>, so the
          indefinite integral of an integrable function need not be
          differentiable everywhere.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-ftc-thomae-zero-primitive">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>h</m> be the Thomae function from
          <xref ref="eg-thomae-function"/>. Since <m>h \ge 0</m> and
          <m>\int_0^1 h=0</m>, part (2) of
          <xref ref="thm-basic-properties-riemann-integral" text="title"/>
          implies that
          <md>
            0 \le \int_0^x h(t)\,dt \le \int_0^1 h(t)\,dt=0
          </md>
          for every <m>x \in [0,1]</m>. Hence the function
          <md>
            H(x)=\int_0^x h(t)\,dt
          </md>
          is identically zero on <m>[0,1]</m>. Therefore <m>H'(x)=0</m> for
          every <m>x \in [0,1]</m>, while <m>h(q) \gt 0</m> for every rational
          <m>q \in [0,1]</m>. So it can happen that the indefinite integral is
          differentiable at a point but its derivative does not equal the
          integrand there.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-two-forms-ftc">
    <title>The Two Forms of the Theorem</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-ftc-first-form">
      <title>Fundamental Theorem of Calculus (First Form)</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>F \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> is differentiable on
          <m>[a,b]</m> and that <m>F' \in R[a,b]</m>. Then
          <md>
            \int_a^b F'(x)\,dx = F(b)-F(a).
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          Since differentiability implies continuity,
          <m>F</m> is continuous on <m>[a,b]</m>. Let
          <m>P=\{x_0,\dots,x_n\}</m> be any partition of <m>[a,b]</m>, and let
          <m>m_i</m> and <m>M_i</m> be the infimum and supremum of
          <m>F'</m> on <m>[x_{i-1},x_i]</m>. By the Mean Value Theorem
          (<xref ref="thm-mean-value-theorem"/>), for each
          <m>i=1,\dots,n</m> there exists <m>t_i \in (x_{i-1},x_i)</m> such
          that
          <md>
            F(x_i)-F(x_{i-1})=F'(t_i)(x_i-x_{i-1}).
          </md>
          Hence
          <md>
            m_i(x_i-x_{i-1})
            \le
            F(x_i)-F(x_{i-1})
            \le
            M_i(x_i-x_{i-1}).
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Summing over <m>i</m> gives
          <md>
            L(P,F')
            \le
            \sum_{i=1}^n \bigl(F(x_i)-F(x_{i-1})\bigr)
            \le
            U(P,F').
          </md>
          The sum in the middle telescopes, so
          <md>
            L(P,F') \le F(b)-F(a) \le U(P,F').
          </md>
        </p>

        <p>
          Since <m>P</m> was arbitrary, we obtain
          <md>
            \underline{\int_a^b} F'
            \le
            F(b)-F(a)
            \le
            \overline{\int_a^b} F'.
          </md>
          Because <m>F'</m> is integrable, the upper and lower integrals are
          equal. Therefore
          <md>
            \int_a^b F'(x)\,dx = F(b)-F(a).
          </md>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>

    <corollary xml:id="cor-newton-leibniz-ftc">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f \colon [a,b] \to \R</m> be continuous, and let <m>F</m> be
          an antiderivative of <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>. Then
          <md>
            \int_a^b f(x)\,dx = F(b)-F(a).
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>

      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="thm-continuous-function-integrable" text="title"/>,
          the function <m>f</m> is Riemann integrable on <m>[a,b]</m>. Since
          <m>F'=f</m>, the conclusion follows from
          <xref ref="thm-ftc-first-form" text="title"/>.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>

    <p>
      When <m>f</m> is continuous, the first form may also be recovered from
      the second form. Indeed, if
      <md>
        F_a(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt,
      </md>
      then <xref ref="thm-ftc-second-form" text="title"/> shows that
      <m>F_a'=f</m>. Hence <m>(F-F_a)'=0</m> on <m>(a,b)</m>, so
      <xref ref="cor-derivative-zero-implies-constant"/> yields
      <m>F(x)=F_a(x)+F(a)</m>. Evaluating at <m>x=b</m> gives
      <m>\int_a^b f = F(b)-F(a)</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="eg-thomae-no-primitive">
      <statement>
        <p>
          The Thomae function is integrable on <m>[0,1]</m>, but it has no
          primitive on <m>[0,1]</m>. Indeed, if <m>H</m> were a primitive of
          <m>h</m>, then by <xref ref="thm-ftc-first-form" text="title"/>,
          <md>
            H(x)-H(0)=\int_0^x h(t)\,dt = 0
          </md>
          for every <m>x \in [0,1]</m>. Thus <m>H</m> would be constant, which
          is impossible because then <m>H'=0</m> everywhere, while
          <m>h(q) \gt 0</m> for rational <m>q</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-ftc-sqrt-not-riemann">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let
          <md>
            H(x)=2\sqrt{x}
            \qquad (x \in [0,1]).
          </md>
          Then <m>H</m> is continuous on <m>[0,1]</m>, and for
          <m>x \in (0,1]</m>,
          <md>
            H'(x)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{x}}.
          </md>
          This derivative is unbounded on <m>[0,1]</m>, so it is not Riemann
          integrable no matter how one defines <m>H'(0)</m>. Thus
          <xref ref="thm-ftc-first-form"/> does not apply.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-ftc-bounded-oscillatory-derivative">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Define
          <md>
            F(x)=
            \begin{cases}
              x^2\sin(1/x) &amp; \text{if } x \ne 0,\\
              0 &amp; \text{if } x=0
            \end{cases}
          </md>
          on <m>[-1,1]</m>. Then <m>F</m> is differentiable on <m>[-1,1]</m>,
          and
          <md>
            F'(x)=
            \begin{cases}
              2x\sin(1/x)-\cos(1/x) &amp; \text{if } x \ne 0,\\
              0 &amp; \text{if } x=0.
            \end{cases}
          </md>
          The derivative is bounded on <m>[-1,1]</m> and is continuous except
          at <m>0</m>, so <m>F'</m> is integrable. By
          <xref ref="thm-ftc-first-form"/>,
          <md>
            \int_{-1}^1 F'(x)\,dx
            =
            F(1)-F(-1)
            =
            \sin(1)-(-\sin(1))
            =
            2\sin(1).
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="eg-ftc-unbounded-oscillatory-derivative">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let
          <md>
            F(x)=
            \begin{cases}
              x^2\cos(1/x^2) &amp; \text{if } x \ne 0,\\
              0 &amp; \text{if } x=0.
            \end{cases}
          </md>
          Then <m>F</m> is differentiable on <m>[0,1]</m>, and
          <md>
            F'(x)=
            \begin{cases}
              2x\cos(1/x^2)+\dfrac{2}{x}\sin(1/x^2) &amp; \text{if } x \ne 0,\\
              0 &amp; \text{if } x=0.
            \end{cases}
          </md>
          The term <m>(2/x)\sin(1/x^2)</m> is unbounded near <m>0</m>, so
          <m>F'</m> is not Riemann integrable on <m>[0,1]</m>. Again,
          <xref ref="thm-ftc-first-form"/> does not apply.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      For a much broader characterization of Riemann integrability, see
      <xref ref="ap-lebesgue-integrability-criterion"/>. In particular,
      <xref ref="thm-lebesgue-integrability-criterion"/> explains why
      bounded functions such as the Thomae function are integrable even though
      they are not continuous everywhere.
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
